  "lab": {
   "goal": [
    {
     "t": "text",
     "text": "See for yourself that a square (clipped) wave is stuffed with "
    },
    {
     "t": "gloss",
     "text": "harmonics",
     "key": "harmonic"
    },
    {
     "t": "text",
     "text": " — and watch a low-pass filter strip them away, exactly as a transmitter's output filter does."
    }
   ],
   "equipment": [
    [
     {
      "t": "text",
      "text": "Oscilloscope with an FFT (Fast Fourier Transform) / spectrum function"
     }
    ],
    [
     {
      "t": "text",
      "text": "Arduino Uno (or any square-wave source)"
     }
    ]
   ],
   "components": [
    [
     {
      "t": "text",
      "text": "A low-pass filter from Chapter 1.8 (an RC or LC low-pass)"
     }
    ],
    [
     {
      "t": "text",
      "text": "Breadboard and jumper wires"
     }
    ],
    [
     {
      "t": "text",
      "text": "A multimeter, to check connections (optional)"
     }
    ]
   ],
   "steps": [
    [
     {
      "t": "text",
      "text": "Set the Arduino to output a 1 kHz "
     },
     {
      "t": "text",
      "text": "square wave on pin 9 (the tone(9, 1000) sketch from Chapter 0.2). A square wave is the harshest, most clipped wave there is — which makes its harmonics easy to see."
     }
    ],
    [
     {
      "t": "text",
      "text": "Probe pin 9 and switch the oscilloscope into "
     },
     {
      "t": "strong",
      "text": "FFT"
     },
     {
      "t": "text",
      "text": " (spectrum) mode. Instead of the square wave in time, you now see it in frequency: a tall spike at 1 kHz — the fundamental — and a row of smaller spikes marching up the axis at 3, 5 and 7 kHz. Those are the harmonics. (A square wave carries only the odd ones; a transmitter's clipping makes all of them.)"
     }
    ],
    [
     {
      "t": "text",
      "text": "Read off the heights. Each harmonic is smaller than the last, but they reach a surprising distance up the band — proof that a clipped wave is anything but pure."
     }
    ],
    [
     {
      "t": "text",
      "text": "Now wire your Chapter 1.8 low-pass filter between pin 9 and the scope probe, with its cutoff set just above 1 kHz. Watch the FFT."
     }
    ],
    [
     {
      "t": "text",
      "text": "The fundamental at 1 kHz barely moves, but the harmonics collapse — the higher the harmonic, the harder it is crushed. You are watching the exact job a transmitter's output filter does, only at audio instead of radio frequencies."
     }
    ]
   ],
   "expected": [
    {
     "t": "text",
     "text": "Without the filter: a tall 1 kHz spike plus a comb of odd harmonics (3, 5, 7 kHz…) stepping downward in height. With the filter: the 1 kHz spike is almost untouched while the harmonics drop away into the noise."
    }
   ],
   "connection": [
    {
     "t": "text",
     "text": "A transmitter's Class C power amplifier clips its wave just as harshly as this square wave is clipped, and makes the very same harmonics — only up at radio frequencies, where they would land on other bands. The output low-pass filter from Section 6 does exactly what you just did on the bench: keep the fundamental, kill the harmonics. (With a real transmitter you would never probe it directly — you would feed a "
    },
    {
     "t": "text",
     "text": "dummy load and tap a tiny, attenuated sample into a spectrum analyser. Full transmitter power destroys instruments.)"
    }
   ],
   "trouble": [
    [
     {
      "t": "text",
      "text": "No FFT mode on your scope: a cheap USB spectrum analyser, or a NanoVNA in spectrum mode, works just as well; failing that, trust the theory — the harmonics are there."
     }
    ],
    [
     {
      "t": "text",
      "text": "Harmonics don't drop: check the filter's cutoff sits above 1 kHz (so the fundamental passes) but below 3 kHz (so the first harmonic is attenuated). An RC filter rolls off gently; an LC filter is sharper."
     }
    ],
    [
     {
      "t": "text",
      "text": "The whole trace is noisy: shorten the probe's ground lead and make sure every breadboard connection is firm."
     }
    ]
   ]
  },
